[{"id":"VH934160","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of the top view of two blocks tied together with a string. At the center of a string, a point labeled C is indicated. Two curved arrows which point in a clockwise direction are drawn between the two boxes, and are labeled Direction of Spin. An arrow labeled Direction of Travel is pointing from the connected boxes to the right.\" height=\"197\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH934160.g01.png\" width=\"265\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure represents the graph of a line in the first quadrant of a coordinate plane. The horizontal axis is labeled “Time, in seconds,” and the numbers 0 through 4.0, in increments of 0.5, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled “System’s Center of Mass Velocity, in meters per second,” and the numbers 0 through 10, in increments of 1, are indicated. The line starts at the point with coordinates 0 seconds, comma 10 meters per second, and moves steadily downward and to the right. It passes through the following three points: with coordinates 1.0 second, comma 8 meters per second; coordinates 2.0 seconds, comma 6 meters per second; and coordinates 3.0 seconds, comma 4 meters per second. The line ends at the point with coordinates 4.0 seconds, comma 2 meters per second. \" height=\"231\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH934160.g02.png\" width=\"350\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two blocks are tied together with a string. They are thrown onto a layer of ice such that they spin around their center of mass <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"C\"><math alttext=\"C\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> as they slide horizontally across the icy surface, as shown in the figure. A graph of the two-block system’s velocity as a function of time is shown. Based on the graph, which of the following claims are correct about the system? Select two answers.</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH934160_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The total displacement of an individual block is zero because it travels in a perfect circle around the center of mass of the system.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The acceleration of the center of mass of the system is constant.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The change in velocity per unit of time for the system’s center of mass changes as time increases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The system’s acceleration vector is opposite to the direction of the system’s velocity vector.</p>"],"answer":["i2","i4"]}]